<!-- SECTION 3 — QFT ON BASIS STATES -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s3">
<div class="section-num">Section 03</div>
<h2>QFT on Computational Basis States</h2>

<p>To understand how to implement the QFT as a circuit, we first compute what it does to a computational basis state |k⟩. By linearity, once we know this, we know what the QFT does to any state.</p>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Key strategy:</strong> It suffices to work out QFT|k⟩ for a generic basis state |k⟩. By linearity of quantum mechanics, QFT(Σ x<sub>k</sub>|k⟩) = Σ x<sub>k</sub> QFT|k⟩. So understanding basis states gives us everything.
</div>

<h3>Computing QFT|k⟩</h3>

<p>The basis state |k⟩ is a vector with a single 1 at position k. Its DFT amplitudes are X<sub>q</sub> = (1/√N) · ω<sub>N</sub><sup>qk</sup>, so:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Step 1:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">QFT|k⟩ = <span class="scalar">1/√N</span> Σ<sub>q=0</sub><sup>N−1</sup> ω<sub>N</sub><sup>qk</sup> |q⟩</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Step 2:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">= <span class="scalar">1/√N</span> (|0⟩ + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>k</sup>|1⟩ + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>2k</sup>|2⟩ + … + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>(N−1)k</sup>|N−1⟩)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>Product form:</strong> Writing k in binary as |k⟩ = |k<sub>n−1</sub>…k₁k₀⟩ and using the binary expansion k = k₀ + 2k₁ + … + 2<sup>n−1</sup>k<sub>n−1</sub>, the QFT output factors into a tensor product of single-qubit states. This is the crucial insight that makes circuit implementation possible!
</div>

<h3>Binary representation</h3>

<p>Write k in binary: k = k₀ + 2k₁ + 4k₂ + … + 2<sup>n−1</sup>k<sub>n−1</sub>, and represent |k⟩ = |k<sub>n−1</sub>…k₁k₀⟩ (MSB first). Then:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Product form:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      QFT|k⟩ ∝ (|0⟩ + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>k</sup>|1⟩) ⊗ (|0⟩ + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>2k</sup>|1⟩) ⊗ … ⊗ (|0⟩ + ω<sub>N</sub><sup>2<sup>n−1</sup>k</sup>|1⟩)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Why factors?</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Each factor (|0⟩ + ω<sup>2<sup>j</sup>k</sup>|1⟩) only depends on a few bits of k because ω<sup>2<sup>j</sup>k</sup> = e<sup>j2π·2<sup>j</sup>k/N</sup> and higher powers of 2 above N wrap around to 1.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Example: N=16, n=4</h3>
<p>For a 4-qubit system N=16, the QFT on |k⟩ = |k₃k₂k₁k₀⟩ gives:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">QFT|k⟩ ∝</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      <span style="text-decoration:underline;">(|0⟩ + ω₁₆<sup>8k</sup>|1⟩)</span> ⊗
      <span style="text-decoration:underline;">(|0⟩ + ω₁₆<sup>4k</sup>|1⟩)</span> ⊗
      <span style="text-decoration:underline;">(|0⟩ + ω₁₆<sup>2k</sup>|1⟩)</span> ⊗
      <span style="text-decoration:underline;">(|0⟩ + ω₁₆<sup>k</sup>|1⟩)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">&nbsp;</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">q₃ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; q₂ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; q₁ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; q₀</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Key insight:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">ω₁₆<sup>8k</sup> = e<sup>jπk</sup> = (−1)<sup>k</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀</sup> &nbsp;&nbsp; (only depends on the last bit!)<br>
    This is because 8k/16 = k/2, so only the parity of k matters, which is k₀ mod 2 = k₀.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Fractional binary notation:</strong> Define 0.k<sub>ℓ</sub>k<sub>ℓ+1</sub>…k<sub>n−1</sub> = k<sub>ℓ</sub>/2 + k<sub>ℓ+1</sub>/4 + … Then ω<sub>N</sub><sup>2<sup>j</sup>k</sup> = e<sup>j2π·0.k<sub>j</sub>k<sub>j+1</sub>…k<sub>n−1</sub></sup>. The j-th qubit factor only depends on bits k<sub>j</sub> through k<sub>n−1</sub> — crucially, NOT on the more significant bits!
</div>

<!-- Exercise 3.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 3.1</span><span class="ex-title">Evaluating ω₈</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>For N = 8, ω₈ = e<sup>j2π/8</sup> = e<sup>jπ/4</sup>. Using cos(π/4) = sin(π/4) = 1/√2, write ω₈ in rectangular form a + bj.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">ω₈ =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a31" placeholder="a+bj" style="width:130px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFreeQFT('a31',['1/√2+j/√2','(1+j)/√2','1/√2 + j/√2'],'fb31')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h31')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h31">ω₈ = cos(π/4) + j·sin(π/4) = 1/√2 + j/√2 = (1+j)/√2 ≈ 0.707 + 0.707j</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb31"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Exercise 3.2 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 3.2</span><span class="ex-title">Bit parity and ω</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>For N = 8, compute ω₈<sup>4k</sup>. Recall ω₈ = e<sup>jπ/4</sup> so ω₈<sup>4</sup> = e<sup>jπ</sup> = −1. Therefore ω₈<sup>4k</sup> = (−1)<sup>k</sup>. In binary k = k₀ + 2k₁ + 4k₂, which single bit determines (−1)<sup>k</sup>?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">The bit is:</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a32" placeholder="k₀ or k₁ or k₂" style="width:120px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFreeQFT('a32',['k0','k₀','k_0','k0 (lsb)'],'fb32')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h32')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h32">(−1)<sup>k</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀+2k₁+4k₂</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>·((−1)²)<sup>k₁</sup>·((−1)⁴)<sup>k₂</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>·1·1. Only k₀ (the least significant bit) matters!</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb32"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 4 — N=4 CIRCUIT -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s4">
<div class="section-num">Section 04</div>
<h2>QFT Circuit for N = 4 (2 qubits)</h2>

<p>Now we build the actual circuit. For N = 4, n = 2 qubits, and k = k₀ + 2k₁, we have |k⟩ = |k₁k₀⟩. The QFT output factors as:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">QFT|k⟩ ∝</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      (|0⟩ + ω₄<sup>2k</sup>|1⟩) ⊗ (|0⟩ + ω₄<sup>k</sup>|1⟩)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Step A:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      ω₄<sup>2k</sup> = (e<sup>j2π/4</sup>)<sup>2k</sup> = e<sup>jπk</sup> = (−1)<sup>k</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>·((−1)<sup>2</sup>)<sup>k₁</sup> = <span class="c-r">(−1)<sup>k₀</sup></span>
      <br><span class="eq-note">Only depends on k₀!</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Step B:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      k = k₀ + 2k₁, so ω₄<sup>k</sup> = ω₄<sup>k₀</sup>·ω₄<sup>2k₁</sup> = ω₄<sup>k₀</sup>·<span class="c-r">(−1)<sup>k₁</sup></span>
      <br><span class="eq-note">Depends on both k₀ and k₁.</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">So QFT|k⟩ ∝</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      <span class="c-b">(|0⟩ + (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>|1⟩)</span> ⊗ <span class="c-g">(|0⟩ + ω₄<sup>k₀</sup>(−1)<sup>k₁</sup>|1⟩)</span>
      &nbsp;&nbsp;= q₁ ⊗ q₀
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Identifying the gates</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Qubit q₁:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      (|0⟩ + (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>|1⟩) → this is exactly <strong>H|k₀⟩</strong>!
      Hadamard maps |0⟩ → (|0⟩+|1⟩)/√2 and |1⟩ → (|0⟩−|1⟩)/√2.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Qubit q₀:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      After H on |k₁⟩ we get (|0⟩ + (−1)<sup>k₁</sup>|1⟩). We then want to multiply the |1⟩ component by ω₄<sup>k₀</sup> = j<sup>k₀</sup> — but <em>only when k₀ = 1</em>. This is a <strong>controlled-phase gate</strong>!
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Definition — Controlled-Phase Gate Ω<sub>N</sub></div>
  <div class="math-block">
    <div class="eq">
      Ω<sub>N</sub> = <span class="mx"><table><tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td class="c-0">0</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="c-0">0</td><td class="c-l">ω<sub>N</sub></td></tr>
      </tbody></table></span>
      <span class="eq-note">&nbsp;&nbsp; Ω<sub>N</sub>|0⟩ = |0⟩, &nbsp; Ω<sub>N</sub>|1⟩ = ω<sub>N</sub>|1⟩</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  When <em>controlled</em> (applied only when the control qubit is |1⟩), it multiplies the |1⟩ amplitude by ω<sub>N</sub> — and does nothing if the control is |0⟩.
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Special case:</strong> Ω₄ = S gate (phase gate, adds phase j to |1⟩). Ω₂ = Z gate. In general, Ω<sub>2<sup>k</sup></sub> is a controlled rotation of angle 2π/2<sup>k</sup> around the Z axis.
</div>

<h3>The N=4 QFT circuit</h3>

<div class="math-block" style="padding:1rem 1.2rem;">
  <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.82rem;line-height:2.2;">
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:50px 1fr;gap:0.2rem 0.5rem;align-items:center;">
      <span style="color:var(--muted);">|k₀⟩</span>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="height:2px;width:1rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="width:1rem;display:flex;justify-content:center;">●</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.15rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);">H</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:1.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">|q₁⟩</span>
      </div>
      <span style="color:var(--muted);">|k₁⟩</span>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.15rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);">H</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--orange);padding:0.15rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--orange);">Ω₄</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:1.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">|q₀⟩</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:0.6rem;font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--muted);">
    Note: The Ω₄ gate on wire |k₁⟩ is controlled by |k₀⟩ (the dot ● above). The output is in <em>reverse order</em>: swap gates are needed if you want |q₀⟩ on top.
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Step-by-step walkthrough for |k⟩ = |1,1⟩ = |11⟩ (k=3)</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Initial:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">|k₀=1⟩|k₁=1⟩ = |1⟩|1⟩</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">H on k₁:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">|1⟩ ⊗ H|1⟩ = |1⟩ ⊗ (|0⟩−|1⟩)/√2</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Ctrl-Ω₄:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Since k₀ = 1, apply Ω₄ to target: |1⟩ ⊗ (|0⟩ − j|1⟩)/√2<br>
    <span class="eq-note">(Ω₄ multiplies |1⟩ by j, leaving |0⟩ unchanged)</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">H on k₀:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">H|1⟩ ⊗ (|0⟩ − j|1⟩)/√2 = (|0⟩−|1⟩)/√2 ⊗ (|0⟩ − j|1⟩)/√2</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Output (q₁,q₀):</div>
    <div class="mstep-body" style="color:var(--green);">= |q₁⟩|q₀⟩ as expected (reversed order — swap to fix)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<canvas id="cvN4circuit" width="560" height="200"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">Interactive N=4 QFT circuit. Select an input basis state to trace the signal through each gate.</div>
<div class="controls" style="gap:0.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap;">
  <span style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--muted);">Input |k⟩ =</span>
  <button class="btn sm active" id="n4btn0" onclick="setN4(0)">|00⟩</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="n4btn1" onclick="setN4(1)">|01⟩</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="n4btn2" onclick="setN4(2)">|10⟩</button>
  <button class="btn sm" id="n4btn3" onclick="setN4(3)">|11⟩</button>
</div>
<div id="n4info" style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--ink2);margin-top:0.5rem;min-height:3rem;line-height:1.9;"></div>

<!-- Exercise 4.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 4.1</span><span class="ex-title">QFT on |00⟩ for N=4</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>For k=0 (|k⟩ = |00⟩), apply the QFT formula. What should be the probability of each basis state |00⟩, |01⟩, |10⟩, |11⟩?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">P(each state) =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a41" placeholder="e.g. 1/4" style="width:100px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFreeQFT('a41',['1/4','0.25','25%'],'fb41')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h41')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h41">QFT|0⟩ = (1/√4)(|0⟩+|1⟩+|2⟩+|3⟩) — uniform superposition. Each amplitude is 1/√4 = 1/2, so each probability is |1/2|² = 1/4.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb41"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 5 — N=8 CIRCUIT -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s5">
<div class="section-num">Section 05</div>
<h2>QFT Circuit for N = 8 (3 qubits)</h2>

<p>Extending to 3 qubits shows the recursive structure of the QFT. With k = k₀ + 2k₁ + 4k₂ we write |k⟩ = |k₂k₁k₀⟩ and factor:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">QFT|k⟩ ∝</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      (|0⟩ + ω₈<sup>4k</sup>|1⟩) ⊗ (|0⟩ + ω₈<sup>2k</sup>|1⟩) ⊗ (|0⟩ + ω₈<sup>k</sup>|1⟩)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Simplify ω₈<sup>4k</sup>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      ω₈<sup>4k</sup> = e<sup>jπk</sup> = (−1)<sup>k</sup> = (−1)<sup>k₀</sup> &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(only k₀ matters)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Simplify ω₈<sup>2k</sup>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      ω₈<sup>2k</sup> = ω₄<sup>k</sup> = ω₄<sup>k₀</sup>·(−1)<sup>k₁</sup> &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(depends on k₀ and k₁)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Simplify ω₈<sup>k</sup>:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      ω₈<sup>k</sup> = ω₈<sup>k₀</sup>·ω₄<sup>k₁</sup>·(−1)<sup>k₂</sup> &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(depends on k₀, k₁, k₂)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>So the full factored form is:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="eq" style="flex-wrap:wrap;gap:0.3rem;">
    <span>QFT|k⟩ ∝</span>
    <span><strong>(|0⟩ + (−1)<sup>k₀</sup>|1⟩)</strong></span>
    <span>⊗</span>
    <span><strong>(|0⟩ + ω₄<sup>k₀</sup>(−1)<sup>k₁</sup>|1⟩)</strong></span>
    <span>⊗</span>
    <span><strong>(|0⟩ + ω₈<sup>k₀</sup>ω₄<sup>k₁</sup>(−1)<sup>k₂</sup>|1⟩)</strong></span>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Circuit structure</h3>

<div class="math-block" style="padding:1rem 1.2rem;">
  <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.79rem;line-height:2.4;">
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:50px 1fr;gap:0.1rem 0.5rem;align-items:center;">
      <span style="color:var(--muted);">|k₀⟩</span>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="min-width:0.8rem;text-align:center;">●</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="min-width:0.8rem;text-align:center;">●</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);">H</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:2rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">|q₂⟩</span>
      </div>
      <span style="color:var(--muted);">|k₁⟩</span>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="min-width:0.8rem;text-align:center;">●</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);">H</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--orange);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--orange);">Ω₄</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:2rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">|q₁⟩</span>
      </div>
      <span style="color:var(--muted);">|k₂⟩</span>
      <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0;">
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.5rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--accent);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);">H</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--orange);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--orange);">Ω₄</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:0.3rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <div style="border:2px solid var(--red);padding:0.1rem 0.4rem;border-radius:3px;font-weight:700;color:var(--red);">Ω₈</div>
        <div style="height:2px;width:2rem;background:var(--ink2);"></div>
        <span style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">|q₀⟩</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:0.5rem;font-size:0.73rem;color:var(--muted);">
    The ● symbols indicate control wires coming from above. Ω₄ = S (phase by j), Ω₈ = T (phase by e<sup>jπ/4</sup>). Output in reverse order.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>Recursive structure:</strong> Notice that QFT₈ contains QFT₄ as a sub-circuit! The bottom two wires (|k₁⟩, |k₂⟩) form a QFT₄ structure, and then |k₀⟩ adds one more stage. In general, QFT<sub>2<sup>n</sup></sub> contains QFT<sub>2<sup>n−1</sup></sub> — this is why the algorithm is efficient.
</div>

<h3>General pattern for n qubits</h3>

<p>For an n-qubit QFT with input |k<sub>n−1</sub>…k₁k₀⟩:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Wire j (from top):</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      receives H, then controlled-Ω<sub>4</sub>, Ω<sub>8</sub>, …, Ω<sub>2<sup>j+1</sup></sub> gates<br>
      controlled by wires above (k₀ is the topmost control wire)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Phase gates:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Ω<sub>N</sub> where N = 2<sup>m</sup> means a phase of ω<sub>2<sup>m</sup></sub> = e<sup>j2π/2<sup>m</sup></sup> applied to |1⟩
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Exercise 5.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 5.1</span><span class="ex-title">Identifying Ω₄ = S gate</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>The gate Ω₄ applies phase ω₄ = j to |1⟩. What standard single-qubit gate has matrix diag(1, j) and therefore equals Ω₄?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">Gate =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a51" placeholder="gate name" style="width:120px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFreeQFT('a51',['s','s gate','phase gate','S'],'fb51')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h51')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h51">The S gate (phase gate) has matrix diag(1, j) = diag(1, ω₄). So Ω₄ = S.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb51"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Exercise 5.2 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 5.2</span><span class="ex-title">Identifying Ω₈ = T gate</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>Similarly, Ω₈ applies phase ω₈ = e<sup>jπ/4</sup> to |1⟩. What standard gate equals Ω₈? (Hint: look at the T (π/8) gate from the earlier notes.)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">Gate =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a52" placeholder="gate name" style="width:120px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFreeQFT('a52',['t','t gate','T','pi/8 gate'],'fb52')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h52')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h52">The T gate (π/8 gate) has matrix diag(1, e<sup>jπ/4</sup>) = diag(1, ω₈). So Ω₈ = T.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb52"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 6 — COMPLEXITY -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s6">
<div class="section-num">Section 06</div>
<h2>Complexity of the QFT</h2>

<p>The QFT's exponential speedup over the classical FFT is one of the most striking results in quantum computing. Let us count the gates precisely.</p>

<h3>Gate count</h3>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label"># Hadamard gates:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">n (one per qubit, applied once)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label"># Controlled-Ω gates:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      Wire 0 (|k₂⟩): 1 controlled gate (Ω₄)<br>
      Wire 1 (|k₁⟩): 2 controlled gates (Ω₄, Ω₈)<br>
      Wire j: j controlled gates<br>
      <strong>Total:</strong> 1 + 2 + … + (n−1) = n(n−1)/2
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Total gates:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">
      n + n(n−1)/2 = n(n+1)/2 ≈ n²/2 &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(quadratic in n!)</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Complexity comparison</div>
  <div class="math-block">
    <div class="mstep">
      <div class="mstep-label">QFT<sub>N</sub>:</div>
      <div class="mstep-body">
        O(n²) = O((log₂ N)²) gates &nbsp;&nbsp; with n = log₂ N qubits
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="mstep">
      <div class="mstep-label">Classical FFT<sub>N</sub>:</div>
      <div class="mstep-body">
        O(N log₂ N) = O(n · 2<sup>n</sup>) operations &nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="eq-note">(exponential in n)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="mstep">
      <div class="mstep-label">Speedup:</div>
      <div class="mstep-body" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">
        n · 2<sup>n</sup> vs n² &nbsp;→&nbsp; exponential speedup!
        <br><span class="eq-note">For n = 1000 (an RSA-like problem): 1000 × 2¹⁰⁰⁰ vs 10⁶ gates</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<canvas id="cvComplexity" width="560" height="220"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">Complexity comparison: QFT gates (blue, n²) vs FFT operations (red, n·2ⁿ). Drag the slider to see the gap grow.</div>
<div class="controls">
  <label>n (qubits) = <input type="range" id="slNcomp" min="1" max="20" value="5" oninput="updateComplexity()"></label>
  <span class="ctrl-val" id="nCompVal">5</span>
</div>
<div id="compInfo" style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--accent);margin-top:0.4rem;min-height:1.5rem;"></div>

<div class="warning">
  <strong>Important caveat:</strong> Despite its O(n²) gate complexity, the QFT does not directly give exponential speedup over FFT for <em>all tasks</em>. Why? Because after the QFT, measuring the state gives only a single random sample from the output distribution — not all N amplitudes simultaneously. The QFT only provides a speedup when used as a subroutine in a cleverly designed algorithm (like Shor's period-finding) where a single sample is enough.
</div>

<!-- Exercise 6.1 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 6.1</span><span class="ex-title">Gate count for n=4</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>For n = 4 qubits (N = 16), how many total gates (H + controlled-Ω) does the QFT require?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">Total gates =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a61" placeholder="?" type="number" style="width:80px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkNumQFT('a61',10,'fb61')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h61')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h61">n = 4. H gates: 4. Controlled-Ω gates: 1+2+3 = 6. Total: 4 + 6 = 10. Formula: n(n+1)/2 = 4·5/2 = 10.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb61"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Exercise 6.2 -->
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 6.2</span><span class="ex-title">Classical vs quantum for n=10</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body">
    <p>For n = 10 (N = 1024): how many operations does the classical FFT need (≈ N log₂ N)? How many gates for QFT (≈ n²)? Compute the ratio FFT/QFT.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">FFT ops ≈</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a62a" placeholder="?" type="number" style="width:100px;">
      <span class="ans-label">QFT gates =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a62b" placeholder="?" type="number" style="width:80px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chk2QFT('a62a',10240,'a62b',100,'fb62')">Check</button>
    </div>
    <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHintQFT('h62')">show hint</button>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h62">FFT: N log₂N = 1024 × 10 = 10240. QFT: n² = 100. Ratio: 102.4 — QFT uses ~100x fewer operations even for small n!</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="fb62"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<script is:inline>
/* ── HELPERS ── */
function goTo(id) { const el=document.getElementById(id); if(el) el.scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth',block:'start'}); }
function showHintQFT(id) { document.getElementById(id).classList.toggle('show'); }

function setFbQFT(id, ok, msg) {
  const el = document.getElementById(id);
  el.className = 'feedback show ' + (ok ? 'ok' : 'no');
  el.textContent = msg;
}
function chkFreeQFT(inputId, accepted, fbId) {
  const v = document.getElementById(inputId).value.trim().toLowerCase().replace(/\s/g,'');
  const ok = accepted.some(a => v === a.toLowerCase().replace(/\s/g,''));
  document.getElementById(inputId).className = 'answer-input ' + (ok?'ok':'no');
  setFbQFT(fbId, ok, ok ? '✓ Correct!' : '✗ Not quite — try again or check the hint.');
}
function chkNumQFT(inputId, target, fbId) {
  const v = parseInt(document.getElementById(inputId).value);
  const ok = v === target;
  document.getElementById(inputId).className = 'answer-input ' + (ok?'ok':'no');
  setFbQFT(fbId, ok, ok ? `✓ Correct! Answer = ${target}.` : `✗ Got ${v}, expected ${target}.`);
}
function chk2QFT(id1, t1, id2, t2, fbId) {
  const v1 = parseInt(document.getElementById(id1).value);
  const v2 = parseInt(document.getElementById(id2).value);
  const ok1 = Math.abs(v1-t1)/t1 < 0.05;
  const ok2 = v2 === t2;
  document.getElementById(id1).className='answer-input '+(ok1?'ok':'no');
  document.getElementById(id2).className='answer-input '+(ok2?'ok':'no');
  setFbQFT(fbId, ok1&&ok2, (ok1&&ok2)?`✓ Correct! FFT≈${t1}, QFT=${t2}.`:`✗ FFT expected≈${t1}, QFT expected=${t2}.`);
}

/* ── QFT DEMO CANVAS ── */
function updateQFTdemo() {
  const P = parseInt(document.getElementById('slPer').value);
  document.getElementById('perVal').textContent = P;
  drawQFTdemo(P);
}
function drawQFTdemo(P) {
  const cv = document.getElementById('cvQFTdemo'); if(!cv) return;
  const ctx = cv.getContext('2d'), W=cv.width, H=cv.height;
  ctx.clearRect(0,0,W,H); ctx.fillStyle='#fafaf8'; ctx.fillRect(0,0,W,H);
  const N=16, half=W/2, pad=30, bw=Math.floor((half-2*pad)/N)-2;
  const accent='#2c5282', orange='#b7530a';

  // time domain
  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.font="10px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='center';
  ctx.fillText('Time domain (period P='+P+')', half/2, 14);

  const x = new Array(N).fill(0).map((_,k)=> k%P===0?1:0);
  const maxH = H-55;
  x.forEach((v,k) => {
    const bx = pad + k*(bw+2);
    ctx.fillStyle = v>0 ? accent : '#e8e4d8';
    ctx.fillRect(bx, H-30-v*maxH*0.7, bw, v*maxH*0.7);
    if(k%4===0){ ctx.fillStyle='#aaa'; ctx.font="8px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.fillText(k, bx+bw/2, H-14); }
  });

  // frequency domain (DFT magnitudes)
  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.textAlign='center';
  ctx.fillText('Frequency domain (QFT magnitude)', half+half/2, 14);

  // Compute DFT magnitudes
  const mags = new Array(N);
  for(let q=0;q<N;q++){
    let re=0,im=0;
    for(let k=0;k<N;k++){
      re += x[k]*Math.cos(2*Math.PI*k*q/N);
      im += x[k]*Math.sin(2*Math.PI*k*q/N);
    }
    mags[q] = Math.sqrt(re*re+im*im)/Math.sqrt(N);
  }
  const maxMag = Math.max(...mags);
  mags.forEach((m,q) => {
    const bx = half + pad + q*(bw+2);
    const h = maxMag>0 ? m/maxMag*maxH*0.7 : 0;
    ctx.fillStyle = h > maxH*0.4 ? orange : '#e8e4d8';
    ctx.fillRect(bx, H-30-h, bw, h);
    if(q%4===0){ ctx.fillStyle='#aaa'; ctx.font="8px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.fillText(q, bx+bw/2, H-14); }
  });

  // divider
  ctx.strokeStyle='#e0ddd5'; ctx.lineWidth=1;
  ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(half,10); ctx.lineTo(half,H-5); ctx.stroke();
}
updateQFTdemo();

/* ── N=4 CIRCUIT CANVAS ── */
let n4state = 0;
function setN4(k) {
  n4state = k;
  [0,1,2,3].forEach(i => {
    const b=document.getElementById('n4btn'+i);
    if(b) b.classList.toggle('active', i===k);
  });
  drawN4(k);
}

function drawN4(k) {
  const cv = document.getElementById('cvN4circuit'); if(!cv) return;
  const ctx = cv.getContext('2d'), W=cv.width, H=cv.height;
  ctx.clearRect(0,0,W,H); ctx.fillStyle='#fafaf8'; ctx.fillRect(0,0,W,H);

  const k0 = k & 1, k1 = (k >> 1) & 1;
  const names = ['|00⟩','|01⟩','|10⟩','|11⟩'];

  // wire y positions
  const y0=65, y1=140, accent='#2c5282', orange='#b7530a', green='#1a6b3a';

  // stage x positions
  const xs = [60, 170, 270, 380, 470];

  ctx.font = "bold 12px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='right'; ctx.textBaseline='middle';
  ctx.fillStyle = '#888'; ctx.fillText('|k₀='+(k0)+'⟩', 52, y0);
  ctx.fillText('|k₁='+(k1)+'⟩', 52, y1);

  // draw wires
  ctx.strokeStyle='#ccc'; ctx.lineWidth=2;
  [y0,y1].forEach(y => {
    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(55,y); ctx.lineTo(W-20,y); ctx.stroke();
  });

  // Ctrl-Ω₄: control at k0=y0, target at k1=y1, moment xs[1]
  // Draw control dot and vertical line
  ctx.fillStyle = '#666'; ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(xs[1], y0, 6, 0, 2*Math.PI); ctx.fill();
  ctx.strokeStyle='#666'; ctx.lineWidth=2;
  ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(xs[1],y0); ctx.lineTo(xs[1],y1-20); ctx.stroke();

  // H on k1 (before Ω₄)
  const drawGate = (x, y, label, col) => {
    ctx.fillStyle='white'; ctx.strokeStyle=col; ctx.lineWidth=2;
    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.roundRect(x-18, y-18, 36, 36, 4); ctx.fill(); ctx.stroke();
    ctx.fillStyle=col; ctx.font="bold 14px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='center'; ctx.textBaseline='middle';
    ctx.fillText(label, x, y);
  };

  drawGate(xs[1], y1, 'H', accent);
  drawGate(xs[2], y1, 'Ω₄', orange);

  // H on k0 (last)
  drawGate(xs[3], y0, 'H', accent);

  // Ctrl line for Ω₄
  ctx.fillStyle = '#666'; ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(xs[2]-30, y0, 6, 0, 2*Math.PI); ctx.fill();
  ctx.strokeStyle='#666'; ctx.lineWidth=2;
  ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(xs[2]-30,y0); ctx.lineTo(xs[2]-30,y1-18); ctx.stroke();
  // connect dot to Ω₄ box
  ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(xs[2]-30, y1); ctx.lineTo(xs[2]-18, y1); ctx.stroke();

  // Output labels
  ctx.fillStyle=green; ctx.font="bold 12px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='left';
  ctx.fillText('|q₁⟩', xs[3]+22, y0);
  ctx.fillText('|q₀⟩', xs[2]+22, y1);

  // Info text
  const phi4 = k0===1 ? 'j' : '1';
  const minus1k0 = k0===1 ? '−' : '+';
  const minus1k1 = k1===1 ? '−' : '+';
  const infos = [
    `Input: |k₀=${k0}⟩|k₁=${k1}⟩ = ${names[k]}`,
    `After H on |k₁⟩: |${k0}⟩ ⊗ (|0⟩${minus1k1}|1⟩)/√2`,
    `After ctrl-Ω₄: |${k0}⟩ ⊗ (|0⟩${minus1k1}${phi4}|1⟩)/√2  [Ω₄ flips by j when k₀=1]`,
    `After H on |k₀⟩: (|0⟩${minus1k0}|1⟩)/√2 ⊗ prev  = |q₁⟩|q₀⟩`,
  ];
  document.getElementById('n4info').innerHTML = infos.join('<br>');
}
drawN4(0);

/* ── COMPLEXITY CANVAS ── */
function updateComplexity() {
  const n = parseInt(document.getElementById('slNcomp').value);
  document.getElementById('nCompVal').textContent = n;
  drawComplexity(n);
  const qft = n*n, fft = n*Math.pow(2,n);
  document.getElementById('compInfo').textContent =
    `n=${n}: QFT gates ≈ ${qft.toFixed(0)} · Classical FFT ops ≈ ${fft.toFixed(0)}  (ratio: ${(fft/qft).toFixed(1)}×)`;
}
function drawComplexity(nCur) {
  const cv = document.getElementById('cvComplexity'); if(!cv) return;
  const ctx = cv.getContext('2d'), W=cv.width, H=cv.height;
  ctx.clearRect(0,0,W,H); ctx.fillStyle='#fafaf8'; ctx.fillRect(0,0,W,H);

  const nMax = 20, PL=50, PR=20, PT=20, PB=45;
  const pW=W-PL-PR, pH=H-PT-PB;

  // find max for scaling
  const maxVal = Math.max(nMax*Math.pow(2,nMax), nMax*nMax);
  // use log scale
  const logMax = Math.log10(nMax*Math.pow(2,nMax)+1);

  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.font="9px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='right';
  [1,2,3,4,5,6].forEach(e => {
    const y = PT+pH - (e/logMax)*pH;
    if(y>PT){ ctx.fillText('10'+e.toString().replace('0','').replace('1','¹').replace('2','²').replace('3','³').replace('4','⁴').replace('5','⁵').replace('6','⁶'), PL-5, y+3);
    ctx.strokeStyle='#eee'; ctx.lineWidth=1; ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(PL,y); ctx.lineTo(W-PR,y); ctx.stroke(); }
  });

  // draw FFT curve (red)
  ctx.strokeStyle='#c0392b'; ctx.lineWidth=2;
  ctx.beginPath();
  for(let n=1;n<=nMax;n++){
    const x = PL + (n-1)/(nMax-1)*pW;
    const v = n*Math.pow(2,n);
    const y = PT+pH - Math.log10(v+1)/logMax*pH;
    n===1?ctx.moveTo(x,y):ctx.lineTo(x,y);
  }
  ctx.stroke();

  // draw QFT curve (blue)
  ctx.strokeStyle='#2c5282'; ctx.lineWidth=2;
  ctx.beginPath();
  for(let n=1;n<=nMax;n++){
    const x = PL + (n-1)/(nMax-1)*pW;
    const v = n*n;
    const y = PT+pH - Math.log10(v+1)/logMax*pH;
    n===1?ctx.moveTo(x,y):ctx.lineTo(x,y);
  }
  ctx.stroke();

  // current n marker
  const nx = PL + (nCur-1)/(nMax-1)*pW;
  ctx.strokeStyle='#888'; ctx.lineWidth=1; ctx.setLineDash([3,3]);
  ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(nx,PT); ctx.lineTo(nx,PT+pH); ctx.stroke(); ctx.setLineDash([]);
  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.font="10px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace"; ctx.textAlign='center';
  ctx.fillText('n='+nCur, nx, PT+pH+14);

  // labels
  ctx.textAlign='left';
  ctx.fillStyle='#c0392b'; ctx.fillText('FFT: O(n·2ⁿ)', PL+5, PT+12);
  ctx.fillStyle='#2c5282'; ctx.fillText('QFT: O(n²)', PL+5, PT+26);

  // x axis labels
  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.textAlign='center';
  [1,5,10,15,20].forEach(n => {
    const x = PL + (n-1)/(nMax-1)*pW;
    ctx.fillText(n, x, PT+pH+28);
  });
  ctx.fillStyle='#888'; ctx.font="9px 'IBM Plex Mono',monospace";
  ctx.fillText('n (number of qubits)', PL+pW/2, PT+pH+42);
}
updateComplexity();
</script>
